" clear=3D"both"> <span id=3D"h4nJa4" class=3D"z-html"><p>The <strong>Volum=
e of an Ellipsoid</strong> formula, V =3D <sup>4</sup>/<sub>3</sub>=E2=8B=
=85=CF=80=E2=8B=85a=E2=8B=85b=E2=8B=85c, computes the volume of an ellipsoi=
d with semi-axes of lengths &nbsp;a, b, and c.<img alt=3D"/attachments/e6cc=
acb1-da27-11e2-8e97-bc764e04d25f/Ellipsoid.png" src=3D"https://www.vcalc.co=
m/attachments/e6ccacb1-da27-11e2-8e97-bc764e04d25f/Ellipsoid.png" style=3D"=
float:right; height:134px; width:218px"></p>=20
<p><strong>INSTRUCTIONS:</strong> &nbsp;Choose units and enter the followin=
g:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>&nbsp;(<strong>a</strong>) &nbsp;semi-axis a.</li>=20
 <li>&nbsp;(<strong>b</strong>) &nbsp;semi-axis b.</li>=20
 <li>&nbsp;(<strong>c</strong>) &nbsp;semi-axis c.</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p><strong>Volume of an Ellipsoid (V):</strong> The volume of the ellipsoid=
 (<strong>v</strong>) is returned in cubic meters. However, the volume can =
be automatically converted to other volume units (e.g. cubic feet, gallons,=
 barrels) via the pull-down menu. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>=20
<h4><span>The Math / Science</span></h4>=20
<p>The formula for the <span class=3D"wikiexternallink"><a href=3D"https://=
www.vcalc.com/wiki/vCalc/Ellipsoid-Volume" target=3D"_self">volume of an el=
lipsoid</a></span> is as follows:</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;V =3D =
<sup>4</sup>/<sub>3</sub>=E2=8B=85=CF=80=E2=8B=85a=E2=8B=85b=E2=8B=85c</p>=
=20
<p>where:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>V is the <span class=3D"wikiexternallink"><a href=3D"https://www.vcalc=
.com/wiki/vCalc/Ellipsoid-Volume" target=3D"_self">volume of the ellipsoid<=
/a></span></li>=20
 <li>a, b and c are the lengths of the semi-axes</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>An ellipsoid is the most general shape in the class that includes:</p>=
=20
<ul>=20
 <li>ellipsoid</li>=20
 <li>oblate spheroid</li>=20
 <li>sphere<br> Note that in each progressing case the number of axes with =
different lengths reduces from 3 in an ellipsoid, to 2 in an oblate spheroi=
d, to one uniform radius in a sphere. &nbsp;Note that this formula is the e=
quivalent to the <span class=3D"wikiexternallink"><a href=3D"https://www.vc=
alc.com/wiki/volume-of-a-sphere" target=3D"_self">volume of a sphere</a></s=
pan>:<br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;V =3D=
 <sup>4</sup>/<sub>3</sub>=E2=8B=85=CF=80=E2=8B=85a=E2=8B=85b=E2=8B=85c<br>=
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;V =3D <sup>4</=
sup>/<sub>3</sub>=E2=8B=85=CF=80=E2=8B=85a=E2=8B=85a=E2=8B=85a<br> &nbsp;&n=
bsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;V =3D <sup>4</sup>/<sub=
>3</sub>=E2=8B=85=CF=80=E2=8B=85a<sup>3</sup> &nbsp;where a is the radius (=
r) of the sphere.</li>=20
</ul>=20
