<p><strong>Volume </strong>is a three dimensional measurement of the amount=
 of space taken up by an object.&nbsp;<img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://www.vcal=
c.com/attachments/e31cac01-f96e-11ed-8f09-bc764e203090/VolAreaHeight.JPG" s=
tyle=3D"float:right; height:116px; width:160px"> Volume units are cubic mea=
surements for solid objects such as cubic inches and cubic meters.&nbsp; Fl=
uids&nbsp;have separate volume units such as liters, fluid ounces, cups, ga=
llons, and barrel.&nbsp;</p>

<p>The volume of an object can measured by the liquid it displaces or&nbsp;=
be calculated by measuring its dimensions and applying those dimensions to =
a formula describing its shape.&nbsp; Many such calculations are available =
in the following list of calculators.&nbsp;</p>

<p>In many cases, the calculators are for a column with a geometric shaped =
base and vertical sides.&nbsp; One basic formula for volume is&nbsp;<a href=
=3D"https://www.vcalc.com/wiki/volume-from-area-and-height">area times a He=
ight</a>&nbsp;when the volume has vertical sides.</p>

